SIMPLE: melanism
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Melanism
<hw>Mel"a*nism</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧l"⟦adot⟧*n⟦icr⟧z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>-anos</grk>, black.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An undue development of dark-colored pigment in the
skin or its appendages; -- the opposite of
<contr>albinism</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A disease; black jaundice. See
<er>Melaena</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanism</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Melanism
<hw>Mel"a*nism</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧l"⟦adot⟧*n⟦icr⟧z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>The character of having a high degree of
pigmentation, as shown in dark skin, eyes, and hair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanistic</ent>⟦br⟧
